Paris in the Middle Ages - Wikipedia|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paris_in_the_Middle_Ages|location of Paris was an important factor in its growth and strategic importance during the Middle Ages. Due to its position at the confluence of the Seine and the rivers Oise, Marne and Yerres, the city was abundantly supplied with food from the surrounding region, which was rich in grain fields and vineyards. The rivers also offered access for trading by boat with other cities in France and locations as far away as Spain and Germany. The Seine, without its stone embankments, was about twice as wide as it is today, and a tributary, the river Bièvre, entered the Seine about where the Jardin des Plantes is today. The largest island in the river, the Île de la Cité("Island of the City"), was  ...    around the city (about 31 kilometers) could sell their grain only to the Paris markets.  In the Middle Ages, the water of the Seine was polluted
